comment:
I've been in a relationship with someone this toxic..

I will never forget when my ex (year long relationship) accused me of cheating when I'd didn't. At 24 years old I was working every day and night to pay the bills and was getting 3 hours of sleep every night from working 3 jobs. She was going to school and living off of my income. I got tired of it and I said "if you're going to falsely accuse me of always cheating than I might as well do it anyways".

She pulled a knife on me in my own kitchen and told me I wouldn't live to tell the story. She even asked me "even if I was to stab you in 'self defense' who do you think the cops would believe you as a man or me?". She even started fake crying with a knife pointed at my stomach while I was doing dishes and started talking to me as if she was speaking to cops afterwards.. saying things  in a sobbing voice like "he was coming at me and I didn't know what to do".

I then planned my escape that weekend afterwards, and moved out.. bought a gun (carry it on me 24/7) and have never looked back. But all I remember thinking all the time is there's women out there who are this crazy, abusive and hide that they think this way. They will hurt or threaten anyone to get what they want.

Still to this day my current wife tells me I have issues trusting people (like friends and family). We even reflected and it took me about a year or two to properly fall asleep overnight in the same bed together since we've started. I always tell her you would too after what I've dealt with.

comment: I know what it is like to be injured, seriously, by someone who is supposed to love you. It is traumatic even if you are injured by  a stranger, but when it is someone you know and love it is disabling.  it is not something you can describe to someone else unless they have experienced it. 30 years ago I lived with an evil man. There were two of him. Many people loved the one man who was clever and charming and very manipulative. Only a few knew the other person. I lived with him for two years but it affected the rest of my life and my subsequent relationships.  When I found out that he had passed away last year I felt a wave of relief. I hadn't seen him in 30 years, yet I still felt that nagging fear that he could come back and do something to wreck my life or hurt me. AS a result of this I took 6 years of Karate which helped a lot but still did not take away that inside fear.  He had the ability to turn people against each other. At first, when he attacked me,  I thought it was an outrageous and inappropriate reaction to something I had done. I didn't know what,  but that was the way my brain was working. It had to be me otherwise why would someone act out like that. Later I came to see that it had nothing to do with me. The day could have gone perfectly; there could be no problems, no disagreements, no issues and suddenly he would explode. THere was no way to avoid it. His mother once told me that if I had just done what he wanted he would not have had to be abusive. You couldn't  go out in public without him suddenly doing something embarrassing. You couldn't go to the grocery store without him throwing a fit because you picked up a loaf of wheat bread and he only liked white bread. and if you wanted to move away from his embarrassing tirade he would yell loudly. "Don't you walk away from me." These people take away your power bit by bit. At the end of my two years with this man I could'nt write a check, drive a car or go to the store by myself, you become powerless. And at that time there was no real substantive help for me in the community. People still do not understand that when you are abused it changes the chemistry in your brain. It messes up your thinking and it takes a year or more to get back to yourself and remember who you really are. IT is very hard. It is a lonely trip. I wish you the very best Mr. Depp.
